, Thanks for the patch, [~kisst2@freemail.hu]. The fix may be right... however, hard code on the path with different OS prefix may not be the best choice. 
I think it is better to use 
{noformat}
  private static final Path TEST_DIR = new Path(System.getProperty("test.build.data", "/tmp"), "terasort");
{noformat}
That should work on Windows given we have many other tests follow the same pattern.
CC [~cnauroth] who is Windows expert.
, Thanks [~djp] for the proposed enhancement. I agree that it is not nice to make the testcase OS specific.

Unfortunately the proposed fix does not resolve the issue, the same error appears:
{noformat}
  TestTeraSort.testTeraSort:92->runTeraSort:67 â•— IO No FileSystem for scheme: C
{noformat}

If we don't want to make distinction in the testcase based on the OS then we need to extend the URI/Scheme
validator to expect windows drive letters in front of the path.

Please let me know your preferred solution.

Thanks!, [~djp] or [~cnauroth]: Could you please take a look on my previous comment and advise? Thanks!, Hello [~kisst2@freemail.hu], thank you for finding this bug and providing a patch.  I agree that ideally the fix should involve going through the {{Path}} class, because that already encapsulates the OS detection and special case handling for the Windows drive spec.  Can you try testing the following?

{code}
  private static final String TEST_DIR = new Path(
      new File(System.getProperty("test.build.data", "/tmp"), "terasort")
          .getAbsoluteFile().toURI()).toString();
{code}

I expect this will work.  Converting the {{File}} to {{URI}} explicitly captures that the scheme is "file:".  Then, passing that {{URI}} through {{Path}} uses the Windows special-case path handling logic that we use throughout Hadoop., Thanks [~cnauroth], your proposed solution works like a charm on Windows & CentOS.

I have attached a new patch to the ticket., | (/) *{color:green}+1 overall{color}* |
